    {"question_text": "What is the output of this Saga pattern implementation for distributed transactions?\n\nclass Saga:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.steps = []\n        self.compensations = []\n    \n    def add_step(self, action, compensation):\n        self.steps.append(action)\n        self.compensations.append(compensation)\n    \n    def execute(self):\n        completed = []\n        for i, step in enumerate(self.steps):\n            try:\n                result = step()\n                completed.append(i)\n            except Exception:\n                for j in reversed(completed):\n                    self.compensations[j]()\n                return 'rolled_back'\n        return 'committed'\n\nsaga = Saga()\nsaga.add_step(lambda: 'ok', lambda: None)\nsaga.add_step(lambda: (_ for _ in ()).throw(Exception('fail')), lambda: None)\nresult = saga.execute()\nprint(result)", "option_a": "committed", "option_b": "rolled_back", "option_c": "Exception", "option_d": "None", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
