    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach to API testing with mocking?\n\nimport responses\nimport requests\n\n@responses.activate\ndef test_api_call():\n    responses.add(\n        responses.GET,\n        'https://api.example.com/users',\n        json={'users': [{'id': 1, 'name': 'Alice'}]},\n        status=200\n    )\n    result = requests.get('https://api.example.com/users')\n    assert result.json()['users'][0]['name'] == 'Alice'\n\nWhat does the @responses.activate decorator do?", "option_a": "It speeds up network requests", "option_b": "It caches responses for reuse", "option_c": "It intercepts actual HTTP requests and returns mocked responses without network calls", "option_d": "It validates response schemas", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to handle streaming responses from an API?\n\ndef stream_response(url):\n    with requests.get(url, stream=True) as response:\n        response.raise_for_status()\n        for chunk in response.iter_content(chunk_size=8192):\n            yield chunk\n\nWhy is stream=True important for large responses?", "option_a": "It makes the download faster", "option_b": "It compresses the response", "option_c": "It prevents loading the entire response into memory at once - data is downloaded in chunks", "option_d": "It enables parallel downloads", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
