    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API request retry with the Retry class from urllib3?\n\nfrom requests.adapters import HTTPAdapter\nfrom urllib3.util.retry import Retry\n\nretry_strategy = Retry(\n    total=3,\n    status_forcelist=[429, 500, 502, 503, 504],\n    allowed_methods=['HEAD', 'GET', 'OPTIONS'],\n    backoff_factor=1\n)\n\nWhat does status_forcelist specify?", "option_a": "HTTP status codes that trigger automatic retry", "option_b": "Status codes that should never be retried", "option_c": "Status codes that are considered successful", "option_d": "Status codes that bypass authentication", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to handle API rate limits using response headers?\n\ndef rate_limited_request(url, session):\n    response = session.get(url)\n    remaining = int(response.headers.get('X-RateLimit-Remaining', 1))\n    reset_time = int(response.headers.get('X-RateLimit-Reset', 0))\n    \n    if remaining == 0:\n        wait_time = reset_time - time.time()\n        if wait_time > 0:\n            time.sleep(wait_time)\n    return response\n\nWhat do X-RateLimit-Remaining and X-RateLimit-Reset typically represent?", "option_a": "Remaining requests in current window, and Unix timestamp when the limit resets", "option_b": "Total limit and time between requests", "option_c": "Requests per second and cooldown duration", "option_d": "Current request count and maximum requests", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement an API client with automatic session management?\n\nclass APISession:\n    def __init__(self, base_url):\n        self.base_url = base_url\n        self.session = requests.Session()\n        self.session.headers.update({'Content-Type': 'application/json', 'Accept': 'application/json'})\n    \n    def __enter__(self):\n        return self\n    \n    def __exit__(self, *args):\n        self.session.close()\n    \n    def get(self, path, **kwargs):\n        return self.session.get(f'{self.base_url}{path}', **kwargs)\n\nWhat is the benefit of using requests.Session() over individual requests.get() calls?", "option_a": "Session persists cookies, connection pooling, and common headers across requests, improving performance", "option_b": "Session is faster for single requests", "option_c": "Session provides automatic retry", "option_d": "Session encrypts all data", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of OAuth2 client credentials flow?\n\ndef get_client_credentials_token(token_url, client_id, client_secret):\n    response = requests.post(token_url, data={\n        'grant_type': 'client_credentials',\n        'client_id': client_id,\n        'client_secret': client_secret,\n        'scope': 'read write'\n    })\n    return response.json()['access_token']\n\nWhat is the grant_type value for machine-to-machine authentication?", "option_a": "client_credentials", "option_b": "authorization_code", "option_c": "password", "option_d": "implicit", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to validate API response schemas in Python?\n\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, ValidationError\n\nclass UserResponse(BaseModel):\n    id: int\n    name: str\n    email: str\n    active: bool\n\ndef fetch_user(user_id):\n    response = requests.get(f'/api/users/{user_id}')\n    try:\n        return UserResponse(**response.json())\n    except ValidationError as e:\n        raise APIError(f'Invalid response: {e}')\n\nWhat benefit does Pydantic provide for API response validation?", "option_a": "Automatic type coercion, validation, and clear error messages for malformed responses", "option_b": "It speeds up API calls", "option_c": "It caches responses", "option_d": "It handles authentication", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement request deduplication in an API client?", "option_a": "Use an idempotency key (unique request ID) sent as a header so the server can identify and deduplicate repeated requests", "option_b": "Never send the same request twice by tracking all URLs", "option_c": "Use timestamps to identify duplicates", "option_d": "The server always handles deduplication automatically", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
