    {"question_text": "What is the difference between synchronous and asynchronous API calls in Python?\n\n# Synchronous\nresponse = requests.get(url)\n\n# Asynchronous\nasync with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n    response = await client.get(url)", "option_a": "Async allows concurrent I/O operations without blocking the event loop, enabling multiple API calls to execute simultaneously", "option_b": "Sync is always faster", "option_c": "Async uses more memory", "option_d": "There is no practical difference", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API request throttling on the client side?\n\nimport time\nfrom collections import deque\n\nclass RateLimiter:\n    def __init__(self, max_requests, time_window):\n        self.max_requests = max_requests\n        self.time_window = time_window\n        self.requests = deque()\n    \n    def acquire(self):\n        now = time.time()\n        while self.requests and self.requests[0] < now - self.time_window:\n            self.requests.popleft()\n        if len(self.requests) >= self.max_requests:\n            sleep_time = self.requests[0] + self.time_window - now\n            time.sleep(sleep_time)\n        self.requests.append(time.time())\n\nWhat algorithm does this implement?", "option_a": "Sliding window rate limiter - tracks request timestamps within a rolling time window", "option_b": "Token bucket", "option_c": "Leaky bucket", "option_d": "Fixed window counter", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
