    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API request batching to reduce network overhead?\n\ndef batch_requests(urls, batch_size=10):\n    results = []\n    for i in range(0, len(urls), batch_size):\n        batch = urls[i:i+batch_size]\n        # Send batch as a single request\n        response = requests.post('/api/batch', json={'requests': batch})\n        results.extend(response.json()['responses'])\n    return results\n\nWhat is the primary benefit of request batching?", "option_a": "Reduces network round trips and connection overhead by combining multiple operations into a single HTTP request", "option_b": "It makes individual requests faster", "option_c": "It provides automatic retry", "option_d": "It enables caching", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement webhook event processing with deduplication?\n\ndef process_webhook(event_id, payload, processed_events):\n    if event_id in processed_events:\n        return {'status': 'already_processed'}\n    \n    # Process the event\n    result = handle_event(payload)\n    processed_events.add(event_id)\n    return {'status': 'processed', 'result': result}\n\nWhy is event deduplication important for webhooks?", "option_a": "Webhook providers may deliver the same event multiple times (at-least-once delivery), so handlers must be idempotent", "option_b": "It speeds up processing", "option_c": "It reduces memory usage", "option_d": "It's required by the HTTP specification", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
