    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement graceful degradation when an API is unavailable?\n\ndef resilient_fetch(url, fallback_value=None, cache=None):\n    try:\n        response = requests.get(url, timeout=5)\n        response.raise_for_status()\n        data = response.json()\n        if cache is not None:\n            cache[url] = data\n        return data\n    except (requests.RequestException, ValueError):\n        if cache and url in cache:\n            return cache[url]\n        return fallback_value\n\nWhat pattern does this implement?", "option_a": "Graceful degradation with fallback - returns cached data or default value when the API is unreachable", "option_b": "Circuit breaker", "option_c": "Load balancing", "option_d": "Request queuing", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API request middleware for adding common headers?\n\nclass HeaderMiddleware:\n    def __init__(self, session, headers):\n        self.session = session\n        session.headers.update(headers)\n    \n    def request(self, method, url, **kwargs):\n        kwargs.setdefault('headers', {}).update({\n            'X-Request-ID': str(uuid.uuid4()),\n            'X-Client-Version': '1.0.0'\n        })\n        return self.session.request(method, url, **kwargs)\n\nWhat is the benefit of request middleware?", "option_a": "It centralizes cross-cutting concerns like logging, auth headers, and request IDs without modifying each call site", "option_b": "It makes requests faster", "option_c": "It caches all responses", "option_d": "It replaces the need for a session", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the difference between API keys and OAuth2 tokens for authentication?", "option_a": "API keys are static credentials identifying the application; OAuth2 tokens are time-limited and can represent delegated user authorization", "option_b": "They are the same thing", "option_c": "API keys are more secure", "option_d": "OAuth2 tokens never expire", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement long-polling for real-time updates from an API?\n\ndef long_poll(url, timeout=30):\n    while True:\n        try:\n            response = requests.get(url, timeout=timeout)\n            if response.status_code == 200:\n                yield response.json()\n            elif response.status_code == 204:\n                continue  # No new data, poll again\n        except requests.Timeout:\n            continue  # Timeout is expected, reconnect\n\nWhat is long-polling?", "option_a": "Client makes a request that the server holds open until new data is available or timeout, then client immediately reconnects", "option_b": "Client polls every 100ms", "option_c": "Server pushes data without client request", "option_d": "Client subscribes to a WebSocket", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},

    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API request timeout with different strategies?\n\n# Connect timeout: time to establish connection\n# Read timeout: time to wait for first byte of response\n# Total timeout: overall time for the entire request\n\nWhich timeout is most important for preventing hanging connections?", "option_a": "Total timeout only", "option_b": "Both connect and read timeouts should be set - connect timeout catches unreachable hosts, read timeout catches slow servers", "option_c": "Only read timeout matters", "option_d": "No timeout is needed if using keep-alive", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of an API SDK method that supports both sync and async usage?\n\nclass APIClient:\n    def __init__(self, api_key):\n        self.api_key = api_key\n        self._sync_client = requests.Session()\n        self._async_client = None\n    \n    def get_users_sync(self):\n        return self._sync_client.get('/users', headers=self._headers).json()\n    \n    async def get_users_async(self):\n        if not self._async_client:\n            import httpx\n            self._async_client = httpx.AsyncClient()\n        resp = await self._async_client.get('/users', headers=self._headers)\n        return resp.json()\n\nWhat is the best practice for SDK design?", "option_a": "Only support synchronous calls", "option_b": "Provide separate sync and async interfaces or use a library that supports both (like httpx which has both sync and async clients)", "option_c": "Only support async calls", "option_d": "Use threading to make sync calls appear async", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What HTTP header should be used to specify the format of the request body?", "option_a": "Accept", "option_b": "Content-Type", "option_c": "X-Format", "option_d": "Transfer-Encoding", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to handle API versioning deprecation in a client library?", "option_a": "Silently use the newest version", "option_b": "Log deprecation warnings when using old API versions and provide migration guides, but continue to function", "option_c": "Immediately throw errors for deprecated versions", "option_d": "Ignore version changes entirely", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement retry logic that respects the Retry-After header?\n\ndef retry_request(url, max_retries=3):\n    for attempt in range(max_retries):\n        response = requests.get(url)\n        if response.status_code == 429:\n            retry_after = response.headers.get('Retry-After')\n            if retry_after:\n                time.sleep(int(retry_after))\n            else:\n                time.sleep(2 ** attempt)\n            continue\n        return response\n    raise Exception('Max retries exceeded')\n\nWhat does the Retry-After header contain?", "option_a": "The number of remaining retries", "option_b": "Either the number of seconds to wait, or an HTTP date indicating when to retry", "option_c": "The maximum request rate", "option_d": "The error message", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of OAuth2 PKCE flow for public clients?\n\nimport hashlib\nimport base64\nimport secrets\n\ndef generate_pkce():\n    code_verifier = secrets.token_urlsafe(32)\n    code_challenge = base64.urlsafe_b64encode(\n        hashlib.sha256(code_verifier.encode()).digest()\n    ).rstrip(b'=').decode()\n    return code_verifier, code_challenge\n\nWhy is PKCE needed for public clients (SPAs, mobile apps)?", "option_a": "To encrypt the response", "option_b": "To prevent authorization code interception attacks since public clients cannot securely store a client secret", "option_c": "To speed up the OAuth flow", "option_d": "To enable offline access", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API client error classification?\n\nclass APIError(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, status_code, message, response=None):\n        self.status_code = status_code\n        self.message = message\n        self.response = response\n        self.retryable = status_code in (429, 500, 502, 503, 504)\n\nWhat is the benefit of classifying errors as retryable vs non-retryable?", "option_a": "It reduces code complexity", "option_b": "It allows retry logic to automatically determine which failures are transient (worth retrying) vs permanent (should fail immediately)", "option_c": "It speeds up error handling", "option_d": "It's required by HTTP specification", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API response pagination using generators for memory efficiency?\n\ndef paginated_fetch(url, page_size=100):\n    page = 1\n    while True:\n        response = requests.get(url, params={'page': page, 'per_page': page_size})\n        data = response.json()\n        if not data:\n            break\n        yield from data\n        page += 1\n\nWhat does 'yield from data' do here?", "option_a": "It returns all data at once", "option_b": "It yields each item individually from the page's list, making the function a lazy generator that doesn't hold all pages in memory", "option_c": "It creates a sub-generator", "option_d": "It filters the data", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},

    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to validate JWT tokens in an API client?\n\nimport jwt\n\ndef validate_token(token, public_key):\n    try:\n        payload = jwt.decode(token, public_key, algorithms=['RS256'])\n        if payload['exp'] < time.time():\n            raise jwt.ExpiredSignatureError\n        return payload\n    except jwt.InvalidTokenError as e:\n        raise AuthError(f'Invalid token: {e}')\n\nWhat should be validated in a JWT token?", "option_a": "Only the expiration time", "option_b": "Signature validity, expiration (exp), issuer (iss), audience (aud), and not-before (nbf) claims", "option_c": "Only the signature", "option_d": "Only the payload structure", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API request queueing for rate-limited endpoints?\n\nimport asyncio\nfrom asyncio import Semaphore\n\nclass RateLimitedClient:\n    def __init__(self, max_concurrent=5):\n        self._semaphore = Semaphore(max_concurrent)\n    \n    async def request(self, url):\n        async with self._semaphore:\n            async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n                return await client.get(url)\n\nWhat does the Semaphore control?", "option_a": "The total number of requests ever made", "option_b": "The maximum number of concurrent in-flight requests, queuing excess requests until a slot is available", "option_c": "The response cache size", "option_d": "The connection timeout", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct status code for a request that requires authentication but no valid credentials were provided?", "option_a": "403 Forbidden", "option_b": "401 Unauthorized", "option_c": "400 Bad Request", "option_d": "407 Proxy Authentication Required", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement GraphQL error handling?\n\nresponse = requests.post(graphql_url, json={'query': query, 'variables': variables})\ndata = response.json()\n\nif 'errors' in data:\n    for error in data['errors']:\n        handle_error(error)\nelif 'data' in data:\n    process_data(data['data'])\n\nHow does GraphQL error handling differ from REST?", "option_a": "GraphQL never returns errors", "option_b": "GraphQL always returns HTTP 200, with errors in the response body alongside partial data - the HTTP status code does not indicate business logic errors", "option_c": "GraphQL uses different HTTP status codes for each error", "option_d": "GraphQL errors are identical to REST errors", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API client connection pooling for high-throughput applications?", "option_a": "Create a new connection for each request", "option_b": "Use a shared requests.Session with HTTPAdapter configured with appropriate pool_connections and pool_maxsize values", "option_c": "Use global variables for connections", "option_d": "Disable keep-alive", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement an API client that handles both JSON and form-encoded request bodies?\n\ndef make_request(url, data, content_type='json'):\n    if content_type == 'json':\n        return requests.post(url, json=data)\n    elif content_type == 'form':\n        return requests.post(url, data=data)\n\nWhat is the key difference between json= and data= parameters in requests?", "option_a": "json= is faster", "option_b": "json= serializes the dict to JSON and sets Content-Type to application/json; data= sends form-encoded data with Content-Type application/x-www-form-urlencoded", "option_c": "data= is for file uploads only", "option_d": "There is no difference", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement automatic pagination following for REST APIs?\n\ndef auto_paginate(url, session, max_pages=100):\n    results = []\n    current_url = url\n    page_count = 0\n    \n    while current_url and page_count < max_pages:\n        response = session.get(current_url)\n        data = response.json()\n        results.extend(data.get('results', []))\n        current_url = data.get('next')\n        page_count += 1\n    \n    return results\n\nWhy is the max_pages guard important?", "option_a": "To improve performance", "option_b": "To prevent infinite loops and excessive memory usage if the API has many pages or a pagination bug", "option_c": "To reduce API costs", "option_d": "It's not important and can be removed", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to handle API SSL/TLS certificate verification?\n\n# Production\nresponse = requests.get(url, verify=True)  # Default\n\n# Development with custom CA\nresponse = requests.get(url, verify='/path/to/ca-bundle.crt')\n\n# NEVER in production\nresponse = requests.get(url, verify=False)\n\nWhy should verify=False never be used in production?", "option_a": "It makes requests slower", "option_b": "It disables SSL certificate verification, making the connection vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks", "option_c": "It causes connection timeouts", "option_d": "It's deprecated in newer versions", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},

    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement retry logic with idempotency keys?\n\ndef safe_retry(url, method, data, max_retries=3):\n    idempotency_key = str(uuid.uuid4())\n    headers = {'Idempotency-Key': idempotency_key}\n    \n    for attempt in range(max_retries):\n        try:\n            response = requests.request(method, url, json=data, headers=headers)\n            if response.status_code < 500:\n                return response\n        except requests.ConnectionError:\n            if attempt == max_retries - 1:\n                raise\n            time.sleep(2 ** attempt)\n    return response\n\nWhy must the same idempotency key be used across all retries?", "option_a": "To make each retry unique", "option_b": "To speed up the server lookup", "option_c": "To bypass rate limiting", "option_d": "So the server knows all retries are the same logical request and only processes it once", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What HTTP status code indicates that the server understood the request but refuses to authorize it?", "option_a": "401 Unauthorized", "option_b": "400 Bad Request", "option_c": "405 Method Not Allowed", "option_d": "403 Forbidden", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API response unwrapping for nested data?\n\ndef unwrap_response(response, path='data'):\n    body = response.json()\n    for key in path.split('.'):\n        if isinstance(body, dict) and key in body:\n            body = body[key]\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(f'Path {path} not found in response')\n    return body\n\nresponse_body = {'status': 'ok', 'data': {'users': [{'id': 1}]}}\n\nWhat would unwrap_response(response, 'data.users') return?", "option_a": "{'users': [{'id': 1}]}", "option_b": "{'id': 1}", "option_c": "'ok'", "option_d": "[{'id': 1}]", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API client middleware for request transformation?\n\nclass RequestMiddleware:\n    def before_request(self, request): return request\n    def after_response(self, response): return response\n\nclass AuthMiddleware(RequestMiddleware):\n    def __init__(self, token):\n        self.token = token\n    def before_request(self, request):\n        request['headers']['Authorization'] = f'Bearer {self.token}'\n        return request\n\nclass LoggingMiddleware(RequestMiddleware):\n    def after_response(self, response):\n        print(f'{response.status_code} - {response.url}')\n        return response\n\nWhat design pattern do these middleware classes implement?", "option_a": "Singleton", "option_b": "Observer", "option_c": "Factory", "option_d": "Chain of Responsibility / Pipeline - each middleware processes and passes the request/response along", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to handle API responses that may return different formats based on content negotiation?\n\ndef parse_response(response):\n    content_type = response.headers.get('Content-Type', '')\n    if 'application/json' in content_type:\n        return response.json()\n    elif 'application/xml' in content_type:\n        return parse_xml(response.text)\n    elif 'text/csv' in content_type:\n        return parse_csv(response.text)\n    else:\n        return response.text\n\nWhat header determines the response format?", "option_a": "Accept", "option_b": "X-Format", "option_c": "Transfer-Encoding", "option_d": "Content-Type in the response headers", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API endpoint discovery using HATEOAS?\n\n# Response includes links to related resources\n{\n    'user': {'id': 1, 'name': 'Alice'},\n    '_links': {\n        'self': '/api/users/1',\n        'posts': '/api/users/1/posts',\n        'friends': '/api/users/1/friends'\n    }\n}\n\nWhat does HATEOAS provide?", "option_a": "Faster API responses", "option_b": "Better caching", "option_c": "Automatic authentication", "option_d": "The client discovers available actions and resources through hyperlinks in responses, reducing coupling to URL structure", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of API client circuit breaker with half-open state testing?\n\nclass CircuitBreaker:\n    def __init__(self, threshold=5, timeout=60):\n        self.threshold = threshold\n        self.timeout = timeout\n        self.state = 'CLOSED'\n        self.failures = 0\n        self.last_failure = 0\n    \n    def execute(self, func, *args):\n        if self.state == 'OPEN':\n            if time.time() - self.last_failure > self.timeout:\n                self.state = 'HALF_OPEN'\n            else:\n                raise CircuitOpenError()\n        # ... execution logic\n\nWhat happens in HALF_OPEN state?", "option_a": "All requests are blocked", "option_b": "All requests are allowed through", "option_c": "The circuit permanently closes", "option_d": "A single test request is allowed through - if it succeeds, the circuit closes; if it fails, it opens again", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API response caching with cache invalidation?\n\nclass CachedAPIClient:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._cache = {}\n    \n    def get(self, url, cache_ttl=300):\n        cached = self._cache.get(url)\n        if cached and time.time() - cached['time'] < cache_ttl:\n            return cached['data']\n        response = requests.get(url)\n        self._cache[url] = {'data': response.json(), 'time': time.time()}\n        return self._cache[url]['data']\n    \n    def invalidate(self, url_pattern):\n        keys_to_remove = [k for k in self._cache if url_pattern in k]\n        for key in keys_to_remove:\n            del self._cache[key]\n\nWhen should cache invalidation be triggered?", "option_a": "Never - let TTL handle it", "option_b": "After every GET request", "option_c": "Only on application restart", "option_d": "After any mutating operation (POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE) that affects the cached resource", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},

    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of API health checking with dependency checks?\n\ndef health_check():\n    checks = {\n        'database': check_db(),\n        'cache': check_cache(),\n        'external_api': check_external_api()\n    }\n    all_healthy = all(checks.values())\n    status_code = 200 if all_healthy else 503\n    return {'status': 'healthy' if all_healthy else 'degraded', 'checks': checks}, status_code\n\nWhat is the purpose of checking dependencies in a health endpoint?", "option_a": "To slow down the response", "option_b": "To log dependency versions", "option_c": "To authenticate the caller", "option_d": "To give load balancers and orchestrators information about whether the service can handle requests", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API versioning through custom headers?\n\nheaders = {\n    'Accept': 'application/vnd.myapp.v2+json',\n    'X-API-Version': '2'\n}\nresponse = requests.get(url, headers=headers)\n\nWhat is the disadvantage of header-based versioning compared to URL-based?", "option_a": "It's slower", "option_b": "It doesn't work with HTTPS", "option_c": "It uses more bandwidth", "option_d": "It's less visible, harder to test in browsers, and responses are less cacheable since the URL is the same across versions", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement request signing for AWS-style API authentication?", "option_a": "Use basic auth with API key", "option_b": "Use a simple Bearer token", "option_c": "Include the key in the URL", "option_d": "Create a canonical request string from method/path/headers/body, sign it with HMAC-SHA256, and include the signature in the Authorization header", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of API request correlation for distributed tracing?\n\ndef make_request_with_tracing(url, parent_trace_id=None):\n    trace_id = parent_trace_id or str(uuid.uuid4())\n    span_id = str(uuid.uuid4())\n    headers = {\n        'X-Trace-ID': trace_id,\n        'X-Span-ID': span_id,\n        'X-Parent-Span-ID': parent_trace_id or ''\n    }\n    return requests.get(url, headers=headers)\n\nWhat is the purpose of distributed tracing headers?", "option_a": "To authenticate requests", "option_b": "To compress responses", "option_c": "To encrypt data", "option_d": "To correlate related requests across multiple services for debugging and observability", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of API client automatic retry with circuit breaker integration?\n\nclass ResilientClient:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.circuit = CircuitBreaker(threshold=5)\n        self.max_retries = 3\n    \n    def request(self, method, url, **kwargs):\n        for attempt in range(self.max_retries):\n            try:\n                response = self.circuit.execute(\n                    lambda: requests.request(method, url, **kwargs)\n                )\n                return response\n            except CircuitOpenError:\n                raise  # Don't retry if circuit is open\n            except requests.RequestException:\n                if attempt == self.max_retries - 1:\n                    raise\n                time.sleep(2 ** attempt)\n\nWhy should CircuitOpenError not be retried?", "option_a": "Because it's a client error", "option_b": "Because retries are expensive", "option_c": "Because the error is permanent", "option_d": "Because the circuit is protecting a failing service - retrying would defeat the purpose of the circuit breaker pattern", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement a REST API client that handles content negotiation automatically?", "option_a": "Always send application/json", "option_b": "Use XML exclusively", "option_c": "Let the server decide without preferences", "option_d": "Set Accept header with quality values (q) to indicate format preferences: Accept: application/json;q=1.0, application/xml;q=0.5", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to test API endpoints that require authentication?\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef authenticated_client():\n    client = APIClient()\n    client.login('test_user', 'test_pass')\n    return client\n\ndef test_protected_endpoint(authenticated_client):\n    response = authenticated_client.get('/api/protected')\n    assert response.status_code == 200\n\nWhat testing pattern is demonstrated here?", "option_a": "Integration testing", "option_b": "Load testing", "option_c": "Fuzz testing", "option_d": "Fixture-based test setup - reusable authenticated state injected into test functions via pytest fixtures", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the difference between webhooks and polling for receiving API events?", "option_a": "Webhooks require more server resources", "option_b": "Polling is always more efficient", "option_c": "They use the same mechanism", "option_d": "Webhooks push events to your endpoint in real-time; polling repeatedly asks the API for changes - webhooks are more efficient but require a publicly accessible endpoint", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement exponential backoff with full jitter?\n\nimport random\n\ndef full_jitter_backoff(base_delay, attempt, max_delay=60):\n    exponential = min(base_delay * (2 ** attempt), max_delay)\n    return random.uniform(0, exponential)\n\nWhy cap the delay with max_delay?", "option_a": "To save memory", "option_b": "To reduce code complexity", "option_c": "It's a Python requirement", "option_d": "To prevent excessively long waits that would make the system appear unresponsive, while still benefiting from exponential growth", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API client request interception for testing?\n\nimport responses\n\n@responses.activate\ndef test_api_integration():\n    responses.add(\n        responses.POST,\n        'https://api.example.com/v1/chat',\n        json={'response': 'Hello!'},\n        status=200\n    )\n    \n    client = ChatClient('https://api.example.com/v1')\n    result = client.send_message('Hi')\n    assert result == 'Hello!'\n    assert len(responses.calls) == 1\n\nWhat does responses.calls provide?", "option_a": "The response bodies", "option_b": "The response headers", "option_c": "The error logs", "option_d": "A list of all intercepted requests, allowing assertions on request URLs, headers, and bodies", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement bulk operations in a REST API client?\n\ndef bulk_create(items, batch_size=50):\n    results = []\n    for i in range(0, len(items), batch_size):\n        batch = items[i:i+batch_size]\n        response = requests.post('/api/bulk', json={'items': batch})\n        results.extend(response.json()['results'])\n    return results\n\nWhat is the advantage of batching over individual requests?", "option_a": "Individual requests are never valid", "option_b": "Batching always guarantees atomicity", "option_c": "Batching is required by REST spec", "option_d": "Batching reduces network overhead, connection setup, and server processing overhead compared to N individual requests", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of API client request deduplication using request fingerprinting?\n\nimport hashlib\n\ndef request_fingerprint(method, url, body=None):\n    content = f'{method}:{url}:{body or \"\"}'\n    return hashlib.md5(content.encode()).hexdigest()\n\nclass DeduplicatedClient:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._in_flight = set()\n    \n    def request(self, method, url, **kwargs):\n        fp = request_fingerprint(method, url, str(kwargs.get('json')))\n        if fp in self._in_flight:\n            raise DuplicateRequestError('Request already in flight')\n        self._in_flight.add(fp)\n        try:\n            return requests.request(method, url, **kwargs)\n        finally:\n            self._in_flight.discard(fp)\n\nWhat scenario does this prevent?", "option_a": "Slow responses", "option_b": "Authentication failures", "option_c": "Network timeouts", "option_d": "Duplicate concurrent requests to the same endpoint (e.g., double-click on submit button)", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API response schema validation with backward compatibility?\n\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Extra\n\nclass UserResponse(BaseModel):\n    id: int\n    name: str\n    email: str\n    \n    class Config:\n        extra = Extra.allow  # Allow unknown fields\n\nWhy use Extra.allow instead of Extra.forbid?", "option_a": "For better performance", "option_b": "To save memory", "option_c": "It's the default behavior", "option_d": "To handle forward compatibility - the API may add new fields in future versions that shouldn't break existing clients", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement an API client that supports request priority queuing?", "option_a": "Send all requests in FIFO order", "option_b": "Use random ordering", "option_c": "Batch all requests and send at once", "option_d": "Use a priority queue (heapq) where high-priority requests are dequeued first, while respecting rate limits", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},

    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement an API client that handles Server-Sent Events (SSE)?\n\ndef stream_sse(url):\n    response = requests.get(url, stream=True)\n    for line in response.iter_lines():\n        if line:\n            decoded = line.decode('utf-8')\n            if decoded.startswith('data: '):\n                yield decoded[6:]\n\nWhat is SSE primarily used for?", "option_a": "Bidirectional communication", "option_b": "File uploads", "option_c": "Server-to-client unidirectional streaming of events over HTTP, commonly used for real-time updates", "option_d": "Database synchronization", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct REST response for an endpoint that accepts a request but processes it asynchronously?\n\nPOST /api/reports/generate\n\nResponse:\n{\n    'status': 'accepted',\n    'job_id': 'abc-123',\n    'status_url': '/api/reports/status/abc-123'\n}\n\nWhat status code and pattern is this?", "option_a": "200 OK with immediate result", "option_b": "201 Created", "option_c": "204 No Content", "option_d": "202 Accepted with a status URL for polling the job result", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement conditional requests using If-Modified-Since?\n\ndef conditional_get(url, session, last_modified_cache):\n    headers = {}\n    if url in last_modified_cache:\n        headers['If-Modified-Since'] = last_modified_cache[url]\n    \n    response = session.get(url, headers=headers)\n    \n    if response.status_code == 304:\n        return None  # Use cached version\n    \n    if 'Last-Modified' in response.headers:\n        last_modified_cache[url] = response.headers['Last-Modified']\n    \n    return response.json()\n\nWhat bandwidth does this save?", "option_a": "None - it always downloads the full response", "option_b": "It saves bandwidth by receiving only a 304 status (no body) when the resource hasn't changed since last fetch", "option_c": "It compresses the response", "option_d": "It reduces the number of headers", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of an API SDK builder pattern for configuration?\n\nclient = (APIClientBuilder()\n    .with_base_url('https://api.example.com')\n    .with_api_key('key-123')\n    .with_timeout(30)\n    .with_retry(max_retries=3)\n    .with_circuit_breaker(threshold=5)\n    .build())\n\nWhat design pattern is this?", "option_a": "Factory", "option_b": "Builder pattern - constructs a complex APIClient step by step with a fluent interface", "option_c": "Singleton", "option_d": "Prototype", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API request rate limiting using the token bucket algorithm?\n\nclass TokenBucket:\n    def __init__(self, rate, capacity):\n        self.rate = rate  # tokens per second\n        self.capacity = capacity\n        self.tokens = capacity\n        self.last_refill = time.time()\n    \n    def consume(self, tokens=1):\n        self._refill()\n        if self.tokens >= tokens:\n            self.tokens -= tokens\n            return True\n        return False\n    \n    def _refill(self):\n        now = time.time()\n        elapsed = now - self.last_refill\n        self.tokens = min(self.capacity, self.tokens + elapsed * self.rate)\n        self.last_refill = now\n\nWhat does 'capacity' represent?", "option_a": "The total number of requests ever allowed", "option_b": "The maximum burst size - tokens can accumulate up to capacity, allowing short bursts above the steady-state rate", "option_c": "The minimum delay between requests", "option_d": "The number of concurrent connections", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to handle API pagination with cursor-based tokens for infinite scrolling?\n\nasync def infinite_scroll(client, endpoint):\n    cursor = None\n    while True:\n        params = {'limit': 20}\n        if cursor:\n            params['after'] = cursor\n        response = await client.get(endpoint, params=params)\n        data = response.json()\n        items = data['items']\n        if not items:\n            break\n        for item in items:\n            yield item\n        cursor = data.get('next_cursor')\n        if not cursor:\n            break\n\nWhat makes cursor-based pagination suitable for infinite scrolling?", "option_a": "It's faster than offset pagination", "option_b": "It maintains a stable position in the dataset regardless of new insertions, preventing duplicate or missed items", "option_c": "It uses less memory", "option_d": "It works offline", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of API client retry with different backoff strategies?\n\nclass BackoffStrategy:\n    def get_delay(self, attempt): raise NotImplementedError\n\nclass ConstantBackoff(BackoffStrategy):\n    def __init__(self, delay): self.delay = delay\n    def get_delay(self, attempt): return self.delay\n\nclass LinearBackoff(BackoffStrategy):\n    def __init__(self, initial): self.initial = initial\n    def get_delay(self, attempt): return self.initial * (attempt + 1)\n\nclass ExponentialBackoff(BackoffStrategy):\n    def __init__(self, base): self.base = base\n    def get_delay(self, attempt): return self.base * (2 ** attempt)\n\nWhat design pattern is used for the backoff strategies?", "option_a": "Observer", "option_b": "Strategy pattern - interchangeable algorithms for delay calculation", "option_c": "Singleton", "option_d": "Factory", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API endpoint mocking for development without a running server?\n\nimport json\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, MagicMock\n\ndef mock_api_response(status_code, body):\n    mock_response = MagicMock()\n    mock_response.status_code = status_code\n    mock_response.json.return_value = body\n    mock_response.headers = {'Content-Type': 'application/json'}\n    return mock_response\n\n@patch('requests.get')\ndef test_fetch_users(mock_get):\n    mock_get.return_value = mock_api_response(200, {'users': []})\n    result = fetch_users()\n    assert result == []\n\nWhat testing principle does this follow?", "option_a": "Integration testing", "option_b": "Isolation - unit tests should not depend on external services; mock the boundaries", "option_c": "Load testing", "option_d": "Acceptance testing", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},

    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API client logging that captures request/response pairs for debugging?\n\nimport logging\n\nclass LoggingSession(requests.Session):\n    def __init__(self, logger=None):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.logger = logger or logging.getLogger(__name__)\n    \n    def request(self, method, url, **kwargs):\n        self.logger.debug(f'Request: {method} {url}')\n        response = super().request(method, url, **kwargs)\n        self.logger.debug(f'Response: {response.status_code}')\n        return response\n\nWhat pattern does this implement?", "option_a": "Factory", "option_b": "Decorator pattern (GoF) - wraps Session with additional logging behavior without changing its interface", "option_c": "Observer", "option_d": "Command", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to handle API pagination when the total count is unknown?\n\ndef fetch_until_empty(url, session, page_param='page', size_param='size', page_size=100):\n    page = 1\n    while True:\n        response = session.get(url, params={page_param: page, size_param: page_size})\n        items = response.json()\n        if not items:\n            break\n        yield from items\n        if len(items) < page_size:\n            break\n        page += 1\n\nHow does this detect the last page?", "option_a": "It checks a 'has_next' field", "option_b": "If the returned items count is less than page_size, it means we've reached the last page", "option_c": "It reads the total from headers", "option_d": "It stops after a fixed number of pages", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of API response streaming for large language model APIs?\n\nasync def stream_llm_response(url, payload):\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        async with client.stream('POST', url, json=payload) as response:\n            async for chunk in response.aiter_text():\n                if chunk.strip():\n                    yield chunk\n\nWhat is the benefit of streaming LLM responses?", "option_a": "It reduces the total response time", "option_b": "It allows displaying partial responses to the user immediately as tokens are generated, improving perceived latency", "option_c": "It uses more bandwidth", "option_d": "It's required by the API", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API endpoint URL construction in a client SDK?\n\nclass APIClient:\n    def __init__(self, base_url):\n        self.base_url = base_url.rstrip('/')\n    \n    def _url(self, path):\n        return f'{self.base_url}/{path.lstrip(\"/\")}'\n    \n    def get_user(self, user_id):\n        return requests.get(self._url(f'/users/{user_id}'))\n    \n    def list_users(self, **filters):\n        return requests.get(self._url('/users'), params=filters)\n\nWhy strip/add slashes in _url()?", "option_a": "For aesthetic reasons", "option_b": "To prevent double-slash issues (e.g., 'https://api.com//users') regardless of how base_url or path are provided", "option_c": "To improve performance", "option_d": "It's a Python requirement", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API response validation using JSON Schema?", "option_a": "Manually check each field", "option_b": "Use jsonschema.validate() to verify the response matches an expected schema, catching structural changes early", "option_c": "Trust the API always returns valid data", "option_d": "Use regex on the JSON string", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What HTTP header indicates the total number of items available in a paginated response?", "option_a": "Content-Length", "option_b": "X-Total-Count or similar custom header conveying the total number of resources available across all pages", "option_c": "Transfer-Encoding", "option_d": "Content-Range", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API client response transformation?", "option_a": "Return raw response objects to callers", "option_b": "Transform API responses into domain objects (data classes/models) so the rest of your code doesn't depend on the API's JSON structure", "option_c": "Always return dictionaries", "option_d": "Return strings", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of adaptive rate limiting that adjusts based on API response headers?\n\nclass AdaptiveRateLimiter:\n    def __init__(self, initial_rate=10):\n        self.rate = initial_rate\n        self.window_remaining = initial_rate\n    \n    def update_from_response(self, response):\n        remaining = response.headers.get('X-RateLimit-Remaining')\n        limit = response.headers.get('X-RateLimit-Limit')\n        if remaining is not None:\n            self.window_remaining = int(remaining)\n        if limit is not None:\n            self.rate = int(limit)\n    \n    def should_throttle(self):\n        return self.window_remaining <= 1\n\nWhat makes this 'adaptive'?", "option_a": "It uses machine learning", "option_b": "It reads the server's actual rate limit state from response headers and adjusts client behavior accordingly, instead of using fixed client-side limits", "option_c": "It changes the timeout", "option_d": "It switches between APIs", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},

    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing API request retry with different strategies for different error types?\n\ndef categorized_retry(func):\n    @functools.wraps(func)\n    def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n        for attempt in range(3):\n            try:\n                return func(*args, **kwargs)\n            except ConnectionError:\n                time.sleep(2 ** attempt)  # Exponential backoff\n            except TimeoutError:\n                time.sleep(1)  # Short fixed delay\n            except RateLimitError as e:\n                time.sleep(e.retry_after)  # Respect server guidance\n        raise MaxRetriesExceeded()\n    return wrapper\n\nWhat principle does error-specific retry behavior follow?", "option_a": "YAGNI", "option_b": "Different failure modes require different recovery strategies - network errors, timeouts, and rate limits have different characteristics", "option_c": "DRY", "option_d": "KISS", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement an async HTTP client with connection pooling in httpx?\n\nasync def fetch_many(urls):\n    limits = httpx.Limits(max_keepalive_connections=20, max_connections=100)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(limits=limits, timeout=30.0) as client:\n        tasks = [client.get(url) for url in urls]\n        return await asyncio.gather(*tasks, return_exceptions=True)\n\nWhat does return_exceptions=True do?", "option_a": "It ignores all exceptions", "option_b": "It returns exceptions as results instead of raising them, allowing successful results to still be collected alongside failures", "option_c": "It logs exceptions", "option_d": "It retries failed requests", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of webhook payload delivery with retry and dead letter queue?\n\nclass WebhookDispatcher:\n    def __init__(self, max_retries=5, dlq=None):\n        self.max_retries = max_retries\n        self.dlq = dlq or []\n    \n    def deliver(self, url, payload):\n        for attempt in range(self.max_retries):\n            try:\n                resp = requests.post(url, json=payload, timeout=10)\n                if 200 <= resp.status_code < 300:\n                    return True\n            except requests.RequestException:\n                pass\n            time.sleep(2 ** attempt)\n        self.dlq.append({'url': url, 'payload': payload})\n        return False\n\nWhat is a dead letter queue (DLQ)?", "option_a": "A queue for deleted messages", "option_b": "A holding area for messages that failed all delivery attempts, allowing later inspection or manual retry", "option_c": "A priority queue", "option_d": "A message encryption mechanism", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement API rate limit handling with a leaky bucket algorithm?", "option_a": "Drop all requests when limit is reached", "option_b": "Process requests at a constant rate, queuing excess requests - the bucket 'leaks' at a fixed rate regardless of input rate", "option_c": "Reset the counter every second", "option_d": "Double the allowed rate on each retry", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output of this code implementing an API client with automatic pagination?\n\nclass PaginatedClient:\n    def __init__(self, base_url):\n        self.base_url = base_url\n        self.session = requests.Session()\n    \n    def fetch_all(self, endpoint, page_size=50):\n        page = 1\n        total_fetched = 0\n        while True:\n            resp = self.session.get(\n                f'{self.base_url}{endpoint}',\n                params={'page': page, 'per_page': page_size}\n            )\n            data = resp.json()\n            yield from data['results']\n            total_fetched += len(data['results'])\n            if total_fetched >= data.get('total', 0):\n                break\n            page += 1\n\nWhat generator method makes each item available individually?", "option_a": "yield data", "option_b": "yield from - it delegates to the iterable, yielding each item from the results list individually", "option_c": "return data", "option_d": "yield data['results']", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the primary purpose of the X-Request-ID header in API communication?", "option_a": "Authentication", "option_b": "Request correlation - it uniquely identifies each request for tracing through logs across multiple services", "option_c": "Rate limiting", "option_d": "Caching", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement graceful shutdown for an API client with pending requests?", "option_a": "Kill all connections immediately", "option_b": "Wait for in-flight requests to complete (with a timeout), then close the session and connection pool", "option_c": "Never close connections", "option_d": "Restart the application", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for handling API breaking changes in a client library?", "option_a": "Ignore the changes and hope for the best", "option_b": "Use semantic versioning in the client, detect API version from responses, and maintain adapters for different API versions", "option_c": "Pin to the oldest API version forever", "option_d": "Rewrite the entire client for each API change", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of request coalescing for reducing duplicate API calls?\n\nclass RequestCoalescer:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._pending = {}\n    \n    async def get(self, url):\n        if url in self._pending:\n            return await self._pending[url]\n        \n        future = asyncio.ensure_future(self._fetch(url))\n        self._pending[url] = future\n        try:\n            return await future\n        finally:\n            del self._pending[url]\n\nWhat does request coalescing achieve?", "option_a": "It speeds up individual requests", "option_b": "Multiple concurrent requests for the same URL share a single in-flight request, reducing load on the API", "option_c": "It caches responses permanently", "option_d": "It compresses requests", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of API response compression negotiation?", "option_a": "Always send compressed requests", "option_b": "Set Accept-Encoding: gzip, deflate in request headers; the server responds with compressed body and Content-Encoding header", "option_c": "Compress the URL", "option_d": "Use smaller JSON keys", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "api_integration"},

    {"question_text": "In Python, what is the correct way to implement the Singleton pattern using __new__?", "option_a": "Override __init__ to return the cached instance", "option_b": "Use a module-level variable", "option_c": "Override __new__ to check if an instance already exists and return it instead of creating a new one", "option_d": "Use a class decorator", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output of this implementation of the Iterator pattern using __iter__ and __next__?\n\nclass Countdown:\n    def __init__(self, start):\n        self.current = start\n    def __iter__(self):\n        return self\n    def __next__(self):\n        if self.current <= 0:\n            raise StopIteration\n        self.current -= 1\n        return self.current + 1\n\nresult = list(Countdown(3))\nprint(result)", "option_a": "[0, 1, 2, 3]", "option_b": "[1, 2, 3]", "option_c": "[3, 2, 1]", "option_d": "[2, 1, 0]", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of the Adapter pattern for wrapping a third-party API client?\n\nclass ThirdPartyClient:\n    def fetch_records(self, filter_str):\n        return [{'record_id': 1, 'record_data': 'data'}]\n\nclass StandardAdapter:\n    def __init__(self, client):\n        self._client = client\n    def get_items(self, query):\n        records = self._client.fetch_records(query)\n        return [{'id': r['record_id'], 'data': r['record_data']} for r in records]\n\nWhat does the adapter do?", "option_a": "It speeds up the third-party client", "option_b": "It caches responses", "option_c": "It converts the third-party interface and data format to match your application's expected interface", "option_d": "It adds retry logic", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output of this implementation of the Decorator pattern for adding features to an agent?\n\nclass BaseAgent:\n    def process(self, msg): return msg\n\nclass MemoryDecorator:\n    def __init__(self, agent):\n        self._agent = agent\n        self.history = []\n    def process(self, msg):\n        self.history.append(msg)\n        context = '\\n'.join(self.history[-5:])\n        return self._agent.process(f'{context}\\n{msg}')\n\nagent = MemoryDecorator(BaseAgent())\nagent.process('hello')\nagent.process('world')\nprint(len(agent.history))", "option_a": "0", "option_b": "1", "option_c": "2", "option_d": "5", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What design pattern is most suitable for implementing an agent that needs to process messages through multiple transformation stages?", "option_a": "Singleton", "option_b": "Observer", "option_c": "Pipeline/Pipes and Filters pattern - each stage transforms the data and passes it to the next", "option_d": "Prototype", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output?\n\nclass PluginManager:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._plugins = {}\n    \n    def register(self, name, plugin):\n        self._plugins[name] = plugin\n    \n    def execute(self, name, *args):\n        if name in self._plugins:\n            return self._plugins[name].run(*args)\n        raise KeyError(f'Plugin {name} not found')\n\nclass UpperPlugin:\n    def run(self, text): return text.upper()\n\nclass ReversePlugin:\n    def run(self, text): return text[::-1]\n\npm = PluginManager()\npm.register('upper', UpperPlugin())\npm.register('reverse', ReversePlugin())\nresult = pm.execute('reverse', pm.execute('upper', 'hello'))\nprint(result)", "option_a": "hello", "option_b": "HELLO", "option_c": "OLLEH", "option_d": "olleh", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What pattern does this code implement for handling different event types in an agent system?\n\nclass EventHandler:\n    _handlers = {}\n    \n    @classmethod\n    def handles(cls, event_type):\n        def decorator(handler_cls):\n            cls._handlers[event_type] = handler_cls\n            return handler_cls\n        return decorator\n    \n    @classmethod\n    def dispatch(cls, event):\n        handler_cls = cls._handlers.get(event['type'])\n        if handler_cls:\n            return handler_cls().handle(event)\n        raise ValueError(f'No handler for {event[\"type\"]}')", "option_a": "Singleton with Factory", "option_b": "Observer with Strategy", "option_c": "Registry pattern with Command dispatch - handlers self-register for specific event types", "option_d": "Template Method", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output of this State pattern implementation?\n\nclass Door:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.state = ClosedState()\n    \n    def open(self):\n        self.state = self.state.open(self)\n        return self\n    \n    def close(self):\n        self.state = self.state.close(self)\n        return self\n\nclass ClosedState:\n    def open(self, door): return OpenState()\n    def close(self, door): return self\n    def __repr__(self): return 'CLOSED'\n\nclass OpenState:\n    def open(self, door): return self\n    def close(self, door): return ClosedState()\n    def __repr__(self): return 'OPEN'\n\nd = Door()\nd.open().close().open()\nprint(d.state)", "option_a": "CLOSED", "option_b": "None", "option_c": "OPEN", "option_d": "ERROR", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output of this Command pattern with undo/redo stack?\n\nclass CommandHistory:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._undo_stack = []\n        self._redo_stack = []\n    \n    def execute(self, command):\n        command.execute()\n        self._undo_stack.append(command)\n        self._redo_stack.clear()\n    \n    def undo(self):\n        if self._undo_stack:\n            cmd = self._undo_stack.pop()\n            cmd.undo()\n            self._redo_stack.append(cmd)\n    \n    def redo(self):\n        if self._redo_stack:\n            cmd = self._redo_stack.pop()\n            cmd.execute()\n            self._undo_stack.append(cmd)\n\nclass AppendCommand:\n    def __init__(self, lst, value):\n        self.lst = lst\n        self.value = value\n    def execute(self): self.lst.append(self.value)\n    def undo(self): self.lst.pop()\n\ndata = []\nhistory = CommandHistory()\nhistory.execute(AppendCommand(data, 'a'))\nhistory.execute(AppendCommand(data, 'b'))\nhistory.undo()\nhistory.redo()\nprint(data)", "option_a": "['a']", "option_b": "[]", "option_c": "['a', 'b']", "option_d": "['b']", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of dependency injection using constructor injection in Python?", "option_a": "Access dependencies through global variables", "option_b": "Import dependencies at the module level only", "option_c": "Pass dependencies as constructor parameters, making them explicit and replaceable", "option_d": "Use metaclasses to inject dependencies", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output of this implementation of the Observer pattern with weak references?\n\nimport weakref\n\nclass WeakObservable:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._observers = []\n    \n    def subscribe(self, observer):\n        self._observers.append(weakref.ref(observer))\n    \n    def notify(self, data):\n        alive = []\n        results = []\n        for ref in self._observers:\n            obs = ref()\n            if obs is not None:\n                alive.append(ref)\n                results.append(obs.on_event(data))\n        self._observers = alive\n        return results\n\nWhat problem do weak references solve in the Observer pattern?", "option_a": "They make notifications faster", "option_b": "They prevent duplicate subscriptions", "option_c": "They prevent memory leaks by allowing observers to be garbage collected when no other strong references exist", "option_d": "They enable async notifications", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output?\n\nclass WorkflowEngine:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.steps = []\n        self.results = []\n    \n    def add_step(self, step_func):\n        self.steps.append(step_func)\n        return self\n    \n    def run(self, initial_data):\n        data = initial_data\n        for step in self.steps:\n            data = step(data)\n            self.results.append(data)\n        return data\n\nengine = WorkflowEngine()\nengine.add_step(lambda x: x.upper())\nengine.add_step(lambda x: x.replace(' ', '_'))\nengine.add_step(lambda x: f'[{x}]')\nresult = engine.run('hello world')\nprint(result)", "option_a": "[hello_world]", "option_b": "[HELLO WORLD]", "option_c": "[HELLO_WORLD]", "option_d": "hello_world", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What pattern does contextlib.contextmanager implement in terms of GoF patterns?", "option_a": "Factory Method", "option_b": "Singleton", "option_c": "Template Method - the with statement provides the algorithm skeleton, and the generator function fills in the specific steps", "option_d": "Observer", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output?\n\nclass Dispatcher:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._routes = {}\n    \n    def route(self, pattern):\n        def decorator(func):\n            self._routes[pattern] = func\n            return func\n        return decorator\n    \n    def dispatch(self, path):\n        for pattern, handler in self._routes.items():\n            if path.startswith(pattern):\n                return handler(path)\n        return '404'\n\napp = Dispatcher()\n\n@app.route('/users')\ndef users_handler(path): return f'users: {path}'\n\n@app.route('/posts')\ndef posts_handler(path): return f'posts: {path}'\n\nprint(app.dispatch('/users/123'))", "option_a": "404", "option_b": "posts: /users/123", "option_c": "users: /users/123", "option_d": "/users/123", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct way to implement the Repository pattern with filtering and sorting?\n\nclass Repository:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._items = []\n    \n    def add(self, item): self._items.append(item)\n    \n    def find(self, **criteria):\n        results = self._items\n        for key, value in criteria.items():\n            results = [i for i in results if i.get(key) == value]\n        return results\n    \n    def find_sorted(self, sort_key, reverse=False, **criteria):\n        results = self.find(**criteria)\n        return sorted(results, key=lambda x: x.get(sort_key, ''), reverse=reverse)\n\nWhat layer of the application should the Repository belong to?", "option_a": "Presentation layer", "option_b": "Transport layer", "option_c": "Domain/Infrastructure layer - it mediates between the domain and data mapping layers", "option_d": "View layer", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output of this implementation of the Chain of Responsibility for request validation?\n\nclass ValidatorChain:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._validators = []\n    \n    def add(self, validator):\n        self._validators.append(validator)\n        return self\n    \n    def validate(self, data):\n        errors = []\n        for v in self._validators:\n            error = v(data)\n            if error:\n                errors.append(error)\n        return errors or None\n\nchain = ValidatorChain()\nchain.add(lambda d: 'missing name' if 'name' not in d else None)\nchain.add(lambda d: 'missing email' if 'email' not in d else None)\nchain.add(lambda d: 'invalid age' if d.get('age', 0) < 0 else None)\n\nresult = chain.validate({'name': 'Alice', 'age': -1})\nprint(result)", "option_a": "None", "option_b": "['missing name']", "option_c": "['missing email', 'invalid age']", "option_d": "['missing name', 'missing email', 'invalid age']", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation of the Mediator pattern for decoupling agent components?\n\nclass AgentMediator:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._components = {}\n    \n    def register(self, name, component):\n        self._components[name] = component\n        component.mediator = self\n    \n    def notify(self, sender, event, data=None):\n        for name, comp in self._components.items():\n            if comp != sender:\n                comp.receive(event, data)\n\nWhat does the mediator prevent?", "option_a": "Memory leaks", "option_b": "Race conditions", "option_c": "Tight coupling between components - they communicate through the mediator instead of directly referencing each other", "option_d": "Infinite loops", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
    {"question_text": "What is the output?\n\nclass Converter:\n    _converters = {}\n    \n    @classmethod\n    def register(cls, from_type, to_type):\n        def decorator(func):\n            cls._converters[(from_type, to_type)] = func\n            return func\n        return decorator\n    \n    @classmethod\n    def convert(cls, value, to_type):\n        from_type = type(value).__name__\n        key = (from_type, to_type)\n        if key in cls._converters:\n            return cls._converters[key](value)\n        raise TypeError(f'No converter for {from_type} -> {to_type}')\n\n@Converter.register('str', 'int')\ndef str_to_int(value): return int(value)\n\n@Converter.register('str', 'list')\ndef str_to_list(value): return list(value)\n\nresult = Converter.convert('hello', 'list')\nprint(result)", "option_a": "['hello']", "option_b": "'hello'", "option_c": "['h', 'e', 'l', 'l', 'o']", "option_d": "TypeError", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},

    {"question_text": "What is the output of this Observer pattern with priority ordering?\n\nclass PriorityBus:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._handlers = []\n    def subscribe(self, handler, priority=0):\n        self._handlers.append((priority, handler))\n        self._handlers.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n    def emit(self, data):\n        return [h(data) for _, h in self._handlers]\n\nbus = PriorityBus()\nbus.subscribe(lambda d: f'low:{d}', priority=1)\nbus.subscribe(lambda d: f'high:{d}', priority=10)\nbus.subscribe(lambda d: f'mid:{d}', priority=5)\nresult = bus.emit('x')\nprint(result[0])", "option_a": "low:x", "option_b": "mid:x", "option_c": "x", "option_d": "high:x", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "design_patterns"},
